    "◻ The following extends the definition of B-isomorphism to arbitrary psites: Definition 4.1.6 Two p-sites a ≡ ( ( One has only to remark that C ○ K (a) = ca(I, κ a), C ○ K (b) = ca(I, κ b), and the lower map C ○K (φ, f) is the B-map (φ, φκa κ b) ∶ ca(I, κ a) → ca(J, κ b).",
    "◻ bpol •/b and Category equivalence to P 2 • -The category bpol •/b is defined as follows: (i) The objects are p-sites, (ii) The set of morphisms of domain a and codomain b is:bpol •/b (a, b) ∶= {φ ∈ J I | ∶ ∃f ∈ B A ∶ (φ, f) ∈ bpol • (a, b)}.",
    "We denote by [φ] b the morphism corresponding to φ (iii) The identity on p-site a ≡ ( (I, A, (A i))) in bpol •/b is the identity id I.",
    "It is worth noting that in this category an isomorphism a → b exists if and only if a and b are B-isomorphic (Definition 4.1.6).",
    "The functor K ∶ bpol • → P 2 • descends to a functor denoted also K ∶ bpol •/b → P 2 •, by positing on object a, K (a) ∶= (I, κ a), and on a morphism [φ] ∈ bpol •/b (a, b), K ([φ]) ∶= φ."
